== 1. Graduate/Junior Analyst

=== Hierarchy Level
0-2 years of experience, entry-level role after completing university (typically commerce/business/finance degree)

=== Key Activities and Responsibilities

*Financial Analysis (50-60%):*
- Analyzing historical financial statements (P&L, balance sheet, cash flow) for target companies
- Building and maintaining detailed Excel financial models
- Performing quality of earnings analysis to identify one-off items, accounting policy impacts, and underlying trading performance
- Analyzing working capital trends and calculating normalized working capital
- Reviewing management accounts and comparing to audited financials
- Extracting and organizing financial data from data rooms
- Performing variance analysis between periods and versus budget/forecast

*Research & Commercial Analysis (20-25%):*
- Researching target company's industry, market position, and competitors
- Analyzing revenue mix, customer concentration, and contract terms
- Reviewing operational KPIs and metrics
- Benchmarking performance against industry peers
- Assessing key business drivers and growth trends
- Conducting customer and supplier analysis
- Reviewing sales pipelines and order books

*Documentation & Deliverables (15-20%):*
- Preparing sections of due diligence reports
- Creating PowerPoint presentations and summary materials
- Maintaining organized working paper files
- Documenting analysis and findings clearly
- Drafting management meeting agendas and questions
- Creating data request lists for target company

*Client & Deal Support (5-10%):*
- Attending management presentations and site visits
- Participating in client update calls
- Supporting senior team members in client meetings
- Coordinating information flow between parties
- Assisting with Q&A processes during deals

=== Required Skills

*Technical:*
- Advanced Excel skills (complex formulas, pivot tables, data manipulation, financial modeling)
- Accounting knowledge (reading financial statements, understanding AASB, identifying adjustments)
- Financial analysis (ratio analysis, trend analysis, margin analysis)
- Valuation concepts (DCF, multiples, basic corporate finance theory)
- Commercial awareness (understanding business models, revenue drivers, cost structures)
- Basic knowledge of M&A process and transaction structures
- Data room platforms (e.g., Ansarada, Intralinks, Datasite)

*Interpersonal:*
- Attention to detail and accuracy
- Time management under tight deadlines
- Clear written communication
- Ability to synthesize complex information
- Professional demeanor in client settings
- Team collaboration and supporting senior colleagues
- Intellectual curiosity and problem-solving
- Resilience under pressure

*Regulatory:*
- Understanding of Australian accounting standards (AASB)
- Basic awareness of Corporations Act provisions
- Confidentiality and professional ethics
- Understanding of continuous disclosure obligations for ASX-listed targets
- Awareness of privacy and data handling requirements

=== Typical Work Modes

*Analytical Work (60-70%):*
- Excel modeling and financial analysis
- Data extraction and organization
- Report drafting and documentation
- Quality control checks

*Meetings (15-25%):*
- Daily team stand-ups and deal status meetings
- Management presentations with target company
- Client update calls (mostly listening/note-taking)
- Site visits to target company operations
- Weekly team meetings and training sessions

*Research & Learning (10-15%):*
- Industry and market research
- Reading prior deal reports for reference
- Internal training sessions
- Reviewing technical guidance and examples
- Staying current on market trends

=== A Day in the Life: Junior Analyst, Transaction Services, Big Four Firm (Sydney)

*8:30am - 9:00am*: Arrive at office. Check emails - new data room file uploaded overnight by Target Co's CFO (monthly management accounts for past 3 months). Download and add to working papers folder. Review today's priorities:
- Complete revenue analysis for Project Atlas (potential private equity buyout of industrial services company)
- Attend 11am management presentation for Project Beacon (vendor due diligence on software business)
- Continue working capital analysis for Project Catalyst (pharmaceutical distribution deal)
- Team status meeting at 4pm

*9:00am - 9:30am*: Team stand-up via video with senior analyst and manager (both working from home today). Discuss Project Atlas progress - Manager wants revenue analysis by 3pm for client call tomorrow. Senior analyst mentions new data room files available for Catalyst. Note any blockers - need clarification from client on treatment of rebates in revenue.

*9:30am - 11:00am*: Deep work on Project Atlas revenue analysis. Company operates three business segments (equipment hire, maintenance services, project work). Building detailed revenue bridge showing:
- Like-for-like growth (excluding acquisitions/disposals)
- Impact of two bolt-on acquisitions made during period
- Price vs volume impacts
- Geographic mix changes (NSW vs QLD vs VIC operations)

Create summary showing organic revenue has been declining 2-3% annually despite headline growth, mainly driven by acquisitions. Equipment hire division showing particular weakness. Flag this as key finding for manager review.

*11:00am - 12:30pm*: Management presentation for Project Beacon at client's office (North Sydney). Attending with Manager and Partner. Vendor due diligence project - client is selling their software business and wants to prepare financial information for buyers. 

Management presents:
- Business model (subscription SaaS, annual contracts with enterprise clients)
- Revenue growth (40% CAGR last 3 years but now slowing to 25%)
- Customer retention (95% retention but churn picking up in past 6 months)
- Product roadmap and R&D investment

Take detailed notes. Notice CFO hedging on recent customer churn - follow-up question needed on reasons for higher churn. Ask question about breakdown of revenue growth between new customers vs expansion of existing - CFO provides helpful detail.

*12:30pm - 1:00pm*: Quick lunch at desk (sandwich from nearby caf√©). Review notes from management presentation. Draft email to manager with initial observations and suggested follow-up questions for management:
- Request detailed churn analysis by customer segment and cohort
- Understand causes of increased churn (competition? product issues? pricing?)
- Detailed pipeline analysis for new customer acquisition
- Understand product development timeline and capex requirements

*1:00pm - 3:00pm*: Continue revenue analysis for Project Atlas. Build supporting schedules showing:
- Revenue by customer type (showing concentration risk with top 10 customers at 45% of revenue)
- Contract duration and renewal analysis
- Pricing trends over time
- Impact of new competitor entering market 18 months ago

Complete draft section for due diligence report explaining revenue performance and key drivers. Email to senior analyst for review. Make note of open items requiring clarification from management.

*3:00pm - 3:30pm*: Shift to Project Catalyst working capital analysis. Review newly uploaded management accounts. Extract payables and receivables data. Begin building working capital bridge showing movement between balance sheet dates:
- Days sales outstanding (DSO) trending up from 45 to 52 days - needs investigation
- Inventory days stable around 35 days
- Days payables outstanding (DPO) reduced from 38 to 32 days - potential cash pressure

Need to understand DSO increase - email senior analyst asking if we can request aged debtors report to understand if this is timing or collection issue.

*3:30pm - 4:00pm*: Prepare for team status meeting. Update project tracker with progress on all three deals:
- Atlas: Revenue analysis complete (pending manager review), working capital analysis 60% complete
- Beacon: Attended management meeting, next steps defined
- Catalyst: Working capital analysis in progress, flagged DSO issue

Review time tracking - 6.5 hours on Atlas, 1.5 hours on Beacon today. Need to allocate 2 hours to Catalyst before end of week.

*4:00pm - 4:45pm*: Weekly team status meeting with broader Transaction Services team (~15 people). Each deal team provides update:
- Our team discusses Atlas, Beacon, Catalyst progress and timelines
- Other teams discuss their deals - helpful to hear about common issues (data quality problems, management availability constraints)
- Partner shares that new deal just won (due diligence for retail business acquisition) - will need analyst support starting next week
- Training session scheduled for Friday on new data analytics tools

*4:45pm - 6:00pm*: Return to Atlas revenue analysis incorporating manager's feedback received via email:
- Add more detail on acquisition integration impacts
- Include sensitivity analysis showing revenue if recent acquisitions excluded
- Add chart showing revenue trend vs industry benchmarks
- Revise commentary to be more balanced (not just negative on organic decline)

Update working papers, ensure all sources clearly documented. Save final version to shared drive.

*6:00pm - 6:30pm*: Catch up on remaining emails and admin tasks:
- Respond to senior analyst's question about Catalyst DSO analysis
- Review tomorrow's calendar - management call for Atlas at 10am (join to take notes)
- Submit timesheet for the week
- Quick check of data rooms for all three projects - no urgent updates

*6:30pm*: Head home. Check phone later in evening - sometimes deals move quickly and urgent requests come through. During critical deal phases (e.g., final week before signing), can work until 8-9pm or occasionally later, but generally 8:30am-6:30pm is typical day for junior analyst outside of deal crunches.

*Evening/Weekend*: Generally evenings and weekends are free, though during intense deal periods (particularly final 1-2 weeks before transaction close or when report deadline approaching) may work some evenings until 8-9pm and potentially weekend hours. Much less demanding than investment banking but still project deadline-driven. Use evening to stay current - read Australian Financial Review articles on recent M&A deals, understand market conditions, build commercial awareness.

