== 2. Senior Analyst / Assistant Manager

=== Hierarchy Level
2-5 years of experience, increasing independence and client interaction

=== Key Activities and Responsibilities
- *Leading Analysis*: Taking ownership of major workstreams (e.g., full quality of earnings analysis, complete working capital assessment)
- *Report Drafting*: Writing substantial sections of due diligence reports with limited supervision
- *Client Interaction*: Participating actively in management meetings, asking probing questions, representing firm on routine client calls
- *Team Management*: Supervising and reviewing work of junior analysts, providing feedback and coaching
- *Quality Control*: Reviewing financial models and analysis for accuracy and completeness
- *Commercial Judgment*: Identifying key deal issues and risks, distinguishing material from immaterial findings
- *Stakeholder Coordination*: Managing information flow between client, target management, lawyers, and other advisors

=== Required Skills Development

Beyond junior analyst skills:
- *Advanced Financial Analysis*: Ability to analyze complex accounting issues, identify earnings quality concerns, assess sustainability of performance
- *Commercial Acumen*: Understanding industry dynamics, competitive positioning, and strategic rationale for transactions
- *Client Management*: Building relationships, managing expectations, communicating findings clearly to non-technical audiences
- *Project Management*: Coordinating workstreams, managing timelines, allocating resources efficiently
- *Leadership*: Managing and developing junior team members, delegating effectively

=== Typical Work Patterns
Similar balance to junior analyst but with more client-facing time (25-35% in meetings) and less pure analytical work (45-55%), plus team management responsibilities (10-15%). Often working on 2-3 deals simultaneously with more complex analysis and greater ownership.

=== Day in the Life - Senior Analyst

Similar structure to junior analyst but with greater autonomy and responsibility. Typical day includes:
- Leading workstream analysis independently (e.g., owning entire quality of earnings analysis)
- Running management Q&A sessions with target company
- Reviewing and providing feedback on junior analysts' work
- Taking more active role in client meetings and calls
- Drafting executive summary sections of reports
- Making commercial judgments about materiality of findings

Hours similar to junior analyst (typically 8:30am-6:30/7pm) but with more variability based on deal intensity - can be 8-9pm during critical weeks.

=== Career Progression
*Within 2-3 years*: Manager role with full deal leadership responsibility, or specialization in specific sector/service line.

