== 3. Manager

=== Hierarchy Level
5-8 years of experience, leading deals and managing client relationships

=== Key Activities and Responsibilities
- *Deal Leadership*: Running entire due diligence engagements from scoping to final report delivery
- *Client Relationships*: Primary day-to-day client contact, managing expectations, presenting findings and recommendations
- *Team Leadership*: Supervising and developing analysts, managing workflow and quality across multiple simultaneous projects
- *Commercial Advisory*: Providing strategic insights beyond financial analysis, advising on transaction structure and negotiation points
- *Business Development*: Supporting Partners in pitching for new work, leveraging existing client relationships
- *Report Quality*: Taking ultimate responsibility for accuracy and quality of deliverables
- *Risk Management*: Identifying and managing engagement risks, ensuring proper documentation and sign-offs

=== Key Skills
Managers need strong business judgment, excellent client management skills, ability to synthesize complex information into clear recommendations, team leadership capabilities, and increasing commercial awareness of transaction dynamics and deal strategy.

=== Typical Work Patterns
Work balance shifts significantly toward client management (35-45%), team leadership (25-30%), and report oversight (20-25%), with less hands-on technical analysis (10-15%). Often managing 3-5 concurrent deals at different stages. Hours typically 8:30am-7/8pm with periodic late nights during deal closings.

=== Career Progression
*Within 2-4 years*: Senior Manager/Director role with broader portfolio, or specialization as subject matter expert (e.g., technology M&A, healthcare deals, vendor due diligence specialist).

